0.header:
Nail fungus may start as a tiny white or orange spot on the nail.

Now, let's see what can be done about it.

1.header:
A,
To start with, are you looking at a nail fungus infection in the first place?

You don't want to assume a nail fungus infection when it could be something serious.

2.header: The nail is getting discolored. Is this why you suspect nail fungus?

4.header: Is the nail surface losing its luster or shine?

6.header: Are there white or orange lines on the side of the nail?

7.header:
Yes?
Start suspecting nail fungus infection.

Suspect nail fungus if:

  • Nail is getting discolored
  • Nail is losing luster or shine on the surface
  • Side of the nail has white or orange lines

8.header: Is the nail turning brittle?

9.header:
Yes?
Suspecting nail fungus infection.

Suspect nail fungus if:

  • Nail is getting discolored
  • Nail is losing luster or shine on the surface
  • Side of the nail has white or orange lines
  • Nail is turning brittle

10.header: Are the outside edges of the nail crumbling?

11.header:
Yes?
May be looking at a nail fungus infection.

Symptoms include:

  • Nail getting discolored
  • Nail losing luster or shine on the surface
  • Side of the nail having white or orange lines
  • Nail turning brittle
  • Outside edges of the nail crumbling.

12.header: Is debris trapped under the nail?

13.header:
Yes?
Looking at a nail fungus infection most likely.

Symptoms include:

  • Nail getting discolored
  • Nail losing luster or shine on the surface
  • Side of the nail having white or orange lines
  • Nail turning brittle
  • Outside edges of the nail crumbling
  • Debris trapped under the nail

14.header: Is the nail getting thicker?

16.header: Is the shape getting distorted?

17.header:
Yes?
More than likely looking at a nail fungus infection.

Suspect nail fungus infection if:

  • Nail is getting discolored
  • Nail is losing luster or shine on the surface
  • Side of the nail has white or orange lines
  • Nail is turning brittle
  • Outside edges of the nail is crumbling
  • Debris is trapped under the nail
  • Nail is getting thicker
  • Shape is getting distorted.

18.header:
A,
Those were the main signs of a nail fungus infection.

If you think you are looking at a nail fungus infection, let's find out if you need to see a doctor for this and how soon.

20.header: Are the tissues surrounding the affected nail red?

22.header: Are they swollen?

23.header:
Seek urgent care or call the doctor.

Here is why:

  • Looking at a serious infection

24.header: Are the tissues filled with pus?

25.header:
Seek urgent care or call the doctor.

Here is why:

  • Looking at infection

26.header: Any red streaks along the skin area?

27.header:
Seek urgent care or call the doctor.

Here is why:

  • May be looking at bacteria infection also.

28.header: Is the nail loosening or lifting up from the skin?

29.header:
Seek urgent care or call the doctor.

Here is why:

  • Over-the-counter creams and ointments generally do not help treat this condition.

  • Prescription anti-fungal medicines taken by mouth may help clear the fungus.
    You will need to take the medicine for about 2 to 3 months for toenails; a shorter time for fingernails.

  • In some cases, the health care provider may remove the nail. Nails grow slowly. Even if treatment is successful, a new, clearer nail may take up to a year to grow in.

30.header: Are you diabetic?

31.header:
Call the doctor.

Here is why:

  • Self care is not adviced.

32.header:
A,
Those were some of the reasons to see a doctor.

Just one more question.

40.header: Is this a reoccurrence or first time nail fungal infection?

41.header:
Seek urgent care or call the doctor.

Here is why:

  • Nail fungus are hard to treat.

  • You will need prescription oral antifungal medications and stay with it all the way.

  • About 50% of people with nail fungal infection get successful treatment first time around with preescription antifungal.

  • In some cases, the health care provider may remove the nail. Nails grow slowly.

  • Even if treatment is successful, a new, clearer nail may take up to a year to grow in.

Would you like to see what a pharmacist recommend for nail fungus infection that is available over-the-counter anyway or see the nearest clinic to you?

42.header:
If it is pretty bad, seeing a healthcare provider will be your best option.

Here is why:

  • The over-the-counter nail fungus medications are not usually successful and will take a long time to work.

  • The time and effort required to treat the nail fungus over-the-counter is going to be far more expensive for you than seeing a doctor.

If it is just starting, you may be able to nip it in the bud.

In this case, we will send you to a pharmacist for recommendation on what is available to use over-the-counter.

Would you like to do this or visit the nearest clinic for evaluation and treatment?

0.header:
A swollen leg may be caused by a leg infection, overweight, medications to name a few.

It could also be a sign of heart failure, kidney failure, or liver failure.



Let's see what you are looking at.

1.header:
It is important to rule out an emergency situation.

We will start by doing that.

2.header:
With this swelling of the leg or foot, are you also experiencing shortness of breath?

Especially when you try to do something?

3.header:
Yes?
This is not looking good.

Having a swollen leg with shortness of breath might signal something serious.

Let's Continue and try to make the best decision we can.

4.header: Any chest pain?

6.header: Is your chest feeling tight?

7.header:
Emergency!
Call 911.

Here is why:

  • May be looking at heart failure.
  • List symptoms of heart failure

Note:
You should only continue if you are not experiencing the question asked.

8.header:
Does it feel as if there is pressure on the chest

With this swollen foot?

9.header:
Emergency situation!
Call 911.

Here is why:

  • May be looking at heart failure.
  • List symptoms of heart failure

Note:
You should only continue if you are not experiencing the question asked.

10.header:
Alright.
Is it just one leg or foot that is swollen?

12.header: Is it getting very painful and you know you did not twist or hurt it?

13.header:
Seek urgent care or call the doctor.

Here is why:

  • May be looking at Deep vein thrombosis (DVT)

Call your doctor especially if you have a predisposing factor (eg, recent surgery, trauma, immobilization, hormone replacement, cancer).
And if it is just one leg that is affected.

14.header:
Do you have a history of liver or kidney disease?

Or heart disease?

15.header:
Seek urgent care or call the doctor.

If it started suddenly, you must seek urgent medical care.

Here is why:

  • Possible blood clot problem which can cause havoc if it gets to the heart.
  • Possible congestive heart failure situation.

16.header:
Is the affected leg or foot red or warm to touch?

And you know you didn't twist it?

17.header:
Seek urgent care or call the doctor.

Here is why:

  • May be looking at cellulitis or other infection.
  • May be looking at a serious inflammation going on.

18.header:
Is it tender and very painful?

And you know you didn't twist it?

19.header:
Seek urgent care or call the doctor.

Here is why:

  • May be looking at cellulitis or other infection.
  • This suggests an inflammatory cause.

20.header: Do you have fever along with this swollen leg or foot?

21.header:
Seek urgent care or call the doctor.

Here is why:

  • Fever along with a painful, swollen joint could be caused by an infected joint.
  • More than one affected joint could mean rheumatic fever.

22.header: Are you pregnant and have a sudden increase in swelling?

23.header:
Call the doctor right away.

Here is why:

  • Severe swelling during pregnancy may be a sign of preeclampsia (also called toxemia).
  • This is a serious condition that includes high blood pressure and swelling.

24.header:
A,
Those were situations of a swollen leg or foot that require emergency care.

If any applied to you, take it seriously and at least call the doctor or seek urgent care.

If none applied to you, let's continue.

30.header:
It is a good idea to find out what may be causing the swelling.

Taking care of the underlying cause will usually solve the problem.

Let's see if we can come up with anything that may be causing it.

31.header: Did you just start taking a new medication?

32.header:
Yes?
Call the pharmacist to see if this is a side effect then let the doctor know about the swelling.

Do not stop taking the medication without the advice of your doctor.

The doctor may give you a diuretic to help with the swelling or change the medication to something else depending on the level of swelling.

33.header: Are you pregnant?

34.header:
Yes?
Most women have some swelling during pregnancy.

More severe swelling during pregnancy may be a sign of preeclampsia (also called toxemia), a serious condition that includes high blood pressure and swelling.

35.header:
A,
Other causes of swelling of the leg or foot are listed below.

This includes:

  • Standing for a long time
  • Long air flight
  • Long car ride

If the swelling is severe or getting worse and you have no idea what is causing it, you should see a doctor.

Not all leg or foot swelling is harmful. Consequences depend mainly on the cause.

Would you like to see what a pharmacist recommend you do to reduce the swelling or visit the nearest urgent care clinic?
